@EXPORTS
deduplicate_frames.py: CLI — perceptual-hash frame deduplication
dedup_report.json: analysis output — JSON with frame groups
concat_list.txt: FFmpeg concat demuxer list (segment paths)

@VARS_CONSTANTS
THRESHOLD: 10 — pHash Hamming distance for "same scene"
FRAMES_DIR: ./epizoda1_screens
HASH_SIZE: 16 (pHash variant)

@FUNCTIONS
deduplicate_frames.main() → void
  purpose: pHash-based frame deduplication
  side-effects: file (writes dedup_report.json, deletes frames with --delete)

@PROCESSES
frame-dedup: glob frame_*.png → pHash(hash_size=16) → consecutive-pair distance check → group similar → keep first → report (+ optional delete)
video-concat: segment MP4s → concat_list.txt → ffmpeg -f concat -i list.txt → final EP01.mp4

@DEPENDENCIES
internal: ./epizoda1_screens/ (extracted frames input) | ./thumbnails/ (YouTube candidates)
external: imagehash, Pillow (PIL), FFmpeg

@STANDARDS
- Dry run by default — --delete flag required for actual removal
- Report written before any deletion (audit trail)
- Segment workflow: EP01 rendered in parts (seg1..seg4) then concat

@WARNINGS
- All .mp4 files .gitignored — not tracked
- epizoda1_screens/ large binary directory (PNGs) — not tracked
- renders/.ruff_cache/ present but should not be committed
- Entire renders/ directory is in .gitignore per root .gitignore

@ARTIFACTS
- EP01.mp4 / EP01-final.mp4 / EP01-preview.mp4 — production outputs
- EP01-seg{1,2,3,4}.mp4 — per-segment renders for concat
- Epizoda1.mp4 / Epizoda1_cast{1,2}.mp4 — earlier cut iterations
